Psychologists coping with unintended births or pregnancies in Tonga are employed

Clinical psychologists that address unintended pregnancies in Tonga are employed professionally, working often in collaboration with clinical obstetricians and midwives, whilst others practise in the community context on a voluntary basis which suits their level of training and expertise. Further research into community and community-based practices that provide unintended pregnancy counseling and services is advised. A full scale project combining both quantitative and qualitative research into the field of unintended pregnancy counseling in Tonga is strongly recommended.
This long-term project strategy should encompass the views and needs of multiple stakeholders, including the specialist health service providers managing unintended pregnancies, the community, the patients clinician’s patients, local community observers and researchers themselves, all of which are critical to ensure that such a project is of value, feasible and appropriate for Tonga.
References Ali, A. B., Chung, K. L., Fraser, M. O., & Domanski, D. (2013). Qualitative evaluation of physicians' perspectives and experiences with restricted access to abortion in Bangladesh, Pakistan and Afghanistan. BMC Health Services Research, 13(1), 1-10.
